ediately after birth","Has two alpha and two beta chains","Has lower oxygen affinity than adult haemoglobin"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin F\u003C/strong\u003E consists of two alpha chains and two gamma chains (\u03b12\u03b32), unlike adult haemoglobin which has \u003Cstrong\u003Etwo alpha and two beta chains\u003C/strong\u003E. This structural difference gives fetal haemoglobin a \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigher oxygen affinity\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ethan adult haemoglobi\u003C/strong\u003En, allowing efficient oxygen transfer across the placenta from mother to fetus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAt birth, \u003Cstrong\u003Efetal haemoglobin comprises approximately 60-80% of total haemoglobin\u003C/strong\u003E. The transition from fetal to adult haemoglobin occurs gradually over the first six months of life, not \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmediately after birth\u003C/strong\u003E. This gradual transition ensures adequate oxygen delivery during the adaptation to extrauterine life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemoglobin F is the primary haemoglobin in fetal life, with higher oxygen affinity than adult haemoglobin.","Haemoglobin F consists of two alpha and two gamma chains.","The switch from fetal to adult haemoglobin occurs gradually during the first six months of life."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48782"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15955"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48782"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T13:22:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T13:23:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8646"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"6333